{{Merge |ETAOI keyboard |date=January 2018 }} {{Infobox software | name = 5-Tiles | title = 5-Tiles | logo = Wear5TILESlogo01.png | logo caption = The 5-Tiles logo | logo size = | logo alt = | screenshot = <!-- Image name is enough --> | caption = | screenshot size = | screenshot alt = | collapsible = | author = | developer = [[ETAOI Systems]] | released = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | discontinued = | latest release version = | latest release date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | latest preview version = | latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | status = | programming language = | operating system = [[Android (operating system)|Android]] | platform = | size = | language = | language count = <!-- Number only --> | language footnote = | genre = [[Virtual keyboard]] | license = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]] | alexa = | website = {{URL|fivetiles.com}} | standard = | AsOf = }}
'''5-Tiles''' is a [[virtual keyboard]] for [[mobile device]]s with [[touchscreen]] that run the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] operating system. It is characterized by needing a small amount of space leaving as much space as possible to the software that needs the keyboard. As the name indicates there are exactly five keys on the keyboard on one line of keys. [[Character (computing)|Characters]] are typed by [[Multi-touch|tap and swipe gestures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webwire.com/ViewPressRel.asp?aId=190926|title=5-TILES Keyboard Goes Free With Beta Launch for Android|author=Lisa Devaney|date=23 September 2014|work=WebWire}}</ref>
The five keys of this keyboard all have different colors to be easily distinguishable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/07/01/long-live-the-nav-key/|title=5-Tiles, The Software Keyboard Targeting Wearables, Picks Up Nokia’s ‘Nav Key’ Inventor As Investor|author=Steve O'Hear|publisher=AOL|work=TechCrunch}}</ref> You have the following options to type a character: * Tap on one of the five buttons * Swipe up or down, beginning on one of the buttons * Swipe a path on the x-axis beginning on one of the buttons changing direction at different buttons and a different number of times—according to the character—until you finally end up on one of the buttons * Making a [[cheat sheet]] visible with a simple swipe gesture and then tapping one of the symbols listed <ref>{{cite web|url=http://fivetiles.com/news/the-5-tiles-keyboard-on-samsung-gear-2-and-gear-neo/|title=The 5-TILES Keyboard on Samsung Gear 2 and Gear Neo – 5-TILES keyboard|work=fivetiles.com}}</ref>
The concept of this keyboard was invented in 2004. The co-founder of the company creating this keyboard, [[Michal Kubacki]], first didn't have skills in [[Computer programming|programming]]. He learned some skills that allowed him to write basic software for testing purposes and to further develop the keyboard. He got in touch with people who helped him creating the product as a virtual keyboard for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices. An early version was downloaded thousands of times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wearables.com/5-tiles-speeds-up-rollout-and-moves-to-free-model/|title=5-Tiles Speeds Up Rollout and Moves to Free Model|work=Wearables.com}}</ref> At the 2013 [[Droidcon]] Demo Camp the company won the second place. It was also awarded in other competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/05/24/5-tiles-keyboard/|title=5-Tiles Keyboard Targets Wearables To Hunt The Post-Qwerty Holy Grail|author=Natasha Lomas|publisher=AOL|work=TechCrunch}}</ref>
